The federal government is waiting for the final position of the National Economic Council (NEC) on the new national minimum wage, Minister of Information, Lai Mohammed has said. Lai told State House Correspondents at the end of an emergency Federal Executive Council (FEC) meeting presided over by President Muhammadu Buhari at the Presidential Villa, Abuja. The minister said the extraordinary FEC meeting was convened to finalise issues on the new national minimum wage bill. Asked to give an insight into what was discussed at the meeting, he said, “I cannot because it’s work in progress,  it would also be discussed by the National Economic Council (NEC)  before we can brief the media.” NEC, which is the nation’s highest economic-decision-making body is chaired by the Vice President Yemi Osinbajo with the 36 state governors, Minister of budget and National Planning, Udoma Udoma and his FCT counterpart, Mohammed Bello as members. The organised labour had made the presentation of the new national minimum wage Bill to the National Assembly as a precondition for shelving its proposed nationwide strike scheduled to commence on January 28. FG, NLC agree to transmit minimum wage bill Jan 23 2016 budget: FEC postpones emergency meeting As January 23 deadline looms